family in Christ — believers who broke bread, prayed, healed, suffered, and worshiped together.</p><p>In Antioch, they were first called <em>Christians</em> (Acts 11:26).</p><p>And it was also in Antioch — this vibrant, cosmopolitan hub where Greek philosophy met Jewish theology, where East collided with West — that their bishop, Ignatius, would craft language that echoed through the centuries.</p><p>But here’s the remarkable part: Ignatius wrote his most influential letters not from a desk or a library, but from a death march. Arrested and …</p>"}